  "prompt": "How long do you have to live on your own (and in poor conditions) to qualify for the Pell Grant? Is the Pell Grant a scholarship for the poor?",
  "response": "The eligibility for the Pell Grant does not depend on how long you have lived on your own or the specific conditions you live in. Instead, the Pell Grant is a need-based grant awarded to undergraduate students from low-income families, primarily determined by the student's and their family's financial situation.\n\nThe Pell Grant is intended to help students who have significant financial need pay for college expenses, including tuition, fees, and other educational costs. To determine financial need and eligibility, the U.S. Department of Education uses the information provided in the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA). Factors considered include family income, family size, the number of family members attending postsecondary institutions, and other financial assets.\n\nIf you are living independently and have low income, this will be reflected in your FAFSA, and it may improve your chances of qualifying for a Pell Grant. However, living conditions specifically are not a direct factor in determining eligibility for the Pell Grant. Instead, the grant aims to provide financial assistance based on overall economic need.",
